def range_preg(x):
    for val in preg_val:
        print("Range of {}".format(x),"for {}".format(val),"Pregnancy is {}".format(D_Final[x][D_Final.Preg==val].max()-D_Final[x][D_Final.Preg==val].min()))
        print("Mean of {}".format(x),"for {}".format(val),"Pregnancy is {}".format(D_Final[x][D_Final.Preg==val].mean()))
        print("Range of {}".format(x),"for {}".format(val),"Pregnancy and is Diabetic is {}".format(D_Final[x][(D_Final.Preg==val)&(D_Final.y==1)].max()-D_Final[x][(D_Final.Preg==val)&(D_Final.y==1)].min()))
        print("Range of {}".format(x),"for {}".format(val),"Pregnancy and is Non-Diabetic is {}".format(D_Final[x][(D_Final.Preg==val)&(D_Final.y==0)].max()-D_Final[x][(D_Final.Preg==val)&(D_Final.y==0)].min()))

We have taken .2 as threshold because we want our recall to be more than precision , i.e we want Diabetic to be classified as Diabetic , hence if you see above in Sensitivity Vs Specificity Section you can see at threshold of .2 sensitivity is more than specificity hence it means we can correctly classify those with diabeties as diabetic .

In health domain we have to be more accurate for predicting those with disease hence we have to make trade off between classifying close to accuracy for diabetic as diabetic

Hence there is a trade off between precision and recall where I have chosen recall over precision.

Model performs well on both training and testing set , hence we can say its fairly generalized model and it doesnt have any issues of over fitting or under fitting
